data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration — `BackgroundProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Must replace with cooperative cancellation |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | `catch` block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Remove entirely |

### Why `Thread.Abort()` Was Removed

It was fundamentally unsafe — it could interrupt code mid-write to shared state, inside `lock` blocks, or during unmanaged interop, causing corruption, deadlocks, and resource leaks that were nearly impossible to debug.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerThread = new Thread(ProcessLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can exit promptly
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work, then exit
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the thread to finish gracefully
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
        {
            bool exited = _workerThread.Join(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            if (!exited)
            {
                // Log a warning — there is no safe forced-kill mechanism.
                // The thread will terminate when the process exits (IsBackground = true).
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

**1. `CancellationToken` replaces `volatile bool` + `Thread.Abort()`**
The token unifies the "please stop" flag *and* the ability to interrupt blocking calls like `BlockingCollection.Take(token)`, `Task.Delay(token)`, `Stream.ReadAsync(token)`, etc. A bare `volatile bool` can't wake a blocked thread.

**2. `GetNextItem(token)` must accept the token**
This is the most important migration step. If the old code blocked inside `GetNextItem()` (e.g., waiting on a queue), cancellation won't work unless the blocking API observes the token. Example:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely, only killable via Abort()
private object GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// After (.NET 8) — exits promptly on cancellation
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
```

**3. `catch (OperationCanceledException)` replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`**
The `when` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from inner code.

**4. No `ResetAbort()` equivalent needed**
`OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — it doesn't auto-rethrow, so `finally` blocks run normally without special handling.

**5. `Thread.Join()` replaces `Thread.Sleep()` + `Abort()`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread; `Sleep` was just hoping. If the thread doesn't exit, `IsBackground = true` ensures it won't keep the process alive.

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| Replacing `Abort()` with `Thread.Interrupt()` | Don't — it only works during `WaitSleepJoin` state and throws `ThreadInterruptedException`, not a clean pattern |
| Forgetting to thread the `CancellationToken` through blocking I/O | The thread hangs on `Stop()` — audit every blocking call |
| Catching bare `OperationCanceledException` without `when` guard | May swallow cancellations from unrelated async work |
| Using `Environment.FailFast()` as a fallback | Kills the entire process, not just the thread |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Minor leak — implement `IDisposable` on the owning class |

### Async Alternative (Preferred for New Code)

If you're migrating anyway, consider `BackgroundService` from `Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting`:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This gives you DI integration, graceful shutdown via `IHostApplicationLifetime`, and proper async I/O — no manual thread management at all.
